arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
1.42 m north south -by- 1.53 m east west.

Locus 17 is the soil below Locus 15 in the bathroom. It is a fine, loose silt with a Munsell of 7.5 YR 4/2 (brown). Like Locus 15 above it, this locus is full of pottery, but also unusually has large amounts of bone and ash. This locus appears to be the result of purposeful dumping in the bathroom, as is also the case for the Locus 14, 15, and 16. Apparently, once the bathroom and anteroom were no longer functional, they were closed off (the door leading into the anteroom was blocked  Locus 25), and filled in. This locus is particularly suggestive of the dumping of refuse here; the bones and ash could easily be the detritus from cooking, conveniently dumped into the remains of the bathroom. The dates for the finds are extremely uniform, and again suggest a single dumping event. With further study by our experts will hopefully give us a fine temporal frame for this event. Locus 15 is therefore phased to Stage 5.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.
